<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is the concrete mix ratio for 3000 PSI?", answer: "A 3000 PSI concrete mix uses a ratio of approximately 1:2:3 (cement:sand:gravel by volume) with a water-cement ratio of 0.55. This is the standard mix for residential foundations, sidewalks, and general-purpose concrete work. For one cubic yard, you need approximately 517 lbs of cement (about 6 bags), 1,100 lbs of sand, and 1,575 lbs of gravel." },
  { question: "What PSI concrete do I need for a driveway?", answer: "Driveways typically require 3500-4000 PSI concrete. The 3500 PSI mix (ratio 1:1.75:2.75) is the minimum recommended for residential driveways, while 4000 PSI is better for driveways that will support heavy vehicles. The higher PSI provides better resistance to freeze-thaw cycles, deicing chemicals, and abrasion from tire traffic." },
  { question: "What does the water-cement ratio mean?", answer: "The water-cement ratio (W/C) is the weight of water divided by the weight of cement in the mix. A lower W/C ratio produces stronger, more durable concrete. For example, a 0.45 W/C ratio means 0.45 pounds of water per pound of cement. Typical ratios range from 0.35 for high-strength concrete to 0.65 for general-purpose mixes. Adding too much water weakens concrete significantly." },
  { question: "How many bags of cement do I need per cubic yard?", answer: "The number of 94-pound cement bags per cubic yard depends on the mix strength. A 3000 PSI mix needs about 5-6 bags per cubic yard, a 4000 PSI mix needs about 6-7 bags, and a 5000 PSI mix needs about 7-8 bags. Higher-strength concrete requires more cement relative to the aggregate, which increases cost but also increases durability and load-bearing capacity." },
  { question: "Can I mix my own concrete for structural work?", answer: "Site-mixed concrete is acceptable for small residential projects like fence posts, small footings, and repairs. For structural work like foundations, slabs, and load-bearing elements, ready-mix concrete from a batch plant is strongly recommended because it is computer-batched for precise proportions, tested for quality, and delivered at the correct consistency. Many building codes require ready-mix for structural elements." }
]) %>

